>It is in fact illegal to shoot and kill wolves in the USA
In Minnesota, this is not because the population needs protecting, but because of lobbying by groups that choose their positions for emotional reasons instead of scientific reasons.

Hunting is helpful for a predator population, not for population control, but for behavioral modification. Wolves that are shy around humans and that avoid settled land are wolves that can coexist with humans, and hunting encourages both. Trophy hunting also creates value in the animals for the humans that have to coexist with the animals. Districts where African big game is legal to hunt have much smaller problems with illegal eradication efforts and with poaching, because knowing some bored white dude is willing to pay $20,000 to kill a lion makes the idea of selling that same lion's testes to a Chinese apocathary for $600 less attractive, and also makes the loss of a cow now and then easier to tolerate.

Trophy hunting with careful management and scientific monitoring is the only hope for macrofauna in the third world.
